12/21/22, 11:09 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <iostream>
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int minDist(string str, int n)
{
    int i = 0;
    while (str[i] == '0')
        i++;

    int firstOccurence = i;

    for (int j = firstOccurence + 1; j < n; j++)
    {
        if (str[j] == '1')
        {
            if ((j - firstOccurence) % 2 == 1)
                return 1;

            firstOccurence = j;
            j++;
        }
    }
    return 2;
}

int main()
{
    // your code goes here

    int t, n;
    cin >> t;
    while (t--)
    {
        string binary;
        cin >> n;
        cin >> binary;

        if (n == 2)
            cout << 1 << endl;

        else
            cout << minDist(binary, n) << endl;
    }
    return 0;
}

1/5/23, 8:59 PM - Vishal Verma: Here is an outline of the Bellman-Ford algorithm for finding the shortest distance between two vertices in a weighted graph:

Initialize an array dist[] of size V, where V is the number of vertices in the graph. Set the value of dist[src] (the source vertex) to 0, and set the values of all other vertices to infinity.

For i = 1 to V-1:
a. For each edge (u, v) with weight w:
i. If dist[u] + w < dist[v], set dist[v] = dist[u] + w.

For each edge (u, v) with weight w:
a. If dist[u] + w < dist[v], return "The graph contains a negative weight cycle."

Return the array dist[], which now holds the shortest distances from src to all other vertices in the graph.

Note: This algorithm can also be used to detect negative weight cycles in the graph. If a negative weight cycle is detected, it means that there is no shortest path between the source vertex and some other vertices in the graph.

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or need further clarification.

1/6/23, 1:18 AM - Harshil B: /*
// Definition for a Node.
class Node {
public:
    int val;
    Node* prev;
    Node* next;
    Node* child;
};
*/

class Solution {
public:
    Node* flatten(Node* head) {
        if(head == NULL){
            return head;
        }
        Node*temp = head;
        while(temp!=NULL){
            if(temp->child){
                Node*ptr = temp->next;
                temp->next = temp->child;
                temp->next->prev = temp;
                temp->child = NULL;

                Node*sudo = temp->next;
                while(sudo->next){
                    sudo = sudo->next;
                }
                sudo->next = ptr;

                if(sudo->next){
                    sudo->next->prev = sudo;
                }
            }
            temp = temp->next;
        }
        return head;
    }
};

1/11/23, 10:39 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
	// your code goes here
	
	int t , n , y;
	
	cin>>t;
	while(t--)
	{
	    cin>>n>>y;
	    vector<int> A(n);
	    int target = 0;
	    
	    for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++)
	    {
	        cin>>A[i];
	        target = target | A[i];
	    }
	    
	    int targetRem;
	    int yRem;
	    int x = 0;
	    int i = 0;
	    
	    while👍
	    {
	        targetRem = target % 2;
	        yRem = y % 2;
	        
	        if(targetRem == 1 && yRem == 0)
	            break;
	       
	        if(targetRem == 0 && yRem == 1)
	        {
	            x += pow(2,i);
	        }
	        
	        target /= 2;
	        y /= 2;
	        i++;
	    }
	    
	    if(y != 0)
	        std::cout << -1 << std::endl;
	    
	    else
	        std::cout << x << std::endl;
	   
	}
	
	
	return 0;
}

1/18/23, 1:15 AM - Vishal Verma: class Solution {
public:
    string customSortString(string order, string s) {
        unordered_map<char, int> map;
        string ans = "";

        // Initializing a map with key value pair 
        // of <character in s , frequency of that character in s  >
        for(int i=0 ; i<s.length() ; i++)
        {
            map[s[i]]++;
        }


        for(auto i:order)
        {
            // Adding all the characters from order at 
            // no. of times there frequency stored in the map
            if(map.find(i) != map.end())
            {
                for(int j=0 ; j<map[i] ; j++)
                    ans += i;
                map[i] = 0;
            }
        }

        // Adding all those characters from s which do not appear in order
        for(auto i:map)
        {
            for(int j=0 ; j<i.second ; j++)
                ans += i.first;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};

1/18/23, 10:48 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int findLeftNear(vector<int> A)
{
    int s=0;
    int e = A.size()-1;
    int ans = 0;
    int mid;
    
    while(s<=e)
    {
        mid = s+(e-s)/2;
        if(A[mid] == 0)
        {
            return 0;
        }
        
        else if(A[mid] < 0)
        {
            ans = A[mid];
            s = mid+1;
        }
        
        else
        {
            e = mid-1;
        }
    }
    return ans;
}

int findRightNear(vector<int> A)
{
    int s=0;
    int e = A.size()-1;
    int ans = 0;
    int mid;
    
    while(s<=e)
    {
        mid = s+(e-s)/2;
        if(A[mid] == 0)
        {
            return 0;
        }
        
        else if(A[mid] < 0)
        {
            s = mid+1;
        }
        
        else
        {
            ans = A[mid];
            e = mid-1;
        }
    }
    return ans;
}


int main() {
	// your code goes here
	int t , n;
	cin>>t;
	while(t--)
	{
	    cin>>n;
	    vector<int> A(n);
	    for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++)
	        cin>>A[i];
	    
	    sort(A.begin() , A.end());
	    int x;
	    int left = findLeftNear(A);
	    int right = findRightNear(A);
	    
	    if(right == left && right == 0)
	        x = -1;
        
        else if(left == 0)
	    {
	        x = right-1;
	    }
	    
	    else if(right == 0)
	    {
	        x = abs(left+1);
	    }
	    
	    else
	    {
	        if(right > abs(left+1))
	            x = abs(left + 1);
	        
	        else if(left < -1*(right - 1))
	            x = right - 1;
	    }
	    
	    cout<<x<<endl;
	}
	
	return 0;
}

2/26/23, 3:39 PM - Harshil B: int solve(int credit , vector<int>&cab,int n){
    int cnt = 0,i=0,sum=0;
    sort(cab.begin(),cab.end());
    while(cab[i]<=credit){
        sum+=cab[i];
        i++;
        if(sum>credit) break;
        else cnt++;
    }
    return cnt;
}

3/1/23, 3:28 PM - Vishal Verma: Hn
3/1/23, 3:29 PM - Vishal Verma: class Solution {
public:

    // Function returns the index of max element
    int max_element(vector<int> &arr)
    {
       int maxi = 0;
       for(int i = 1 ; i<arr.size() ; i++)
       {
           if(arr[maxi]<arr[i])
                maxi = i;
       } 
       return maxi;
    }

    string frequencySort(string s) {

        string ans = "";

        // Making frequency Array of size 123 (0-122 ASCII value)
        vector<int> frequencyArr(123);
        for(auto x:s)
        {
            frequencyArr[x]++;
        }

        int maxi = max_element(frequencyArr);

        while(frequencyArr[maxi])
        {
            // Adding the character, no. of times its frequency in the array
            while(frequencyArr[maxi]--)
            {
                ans += (char)maxi;
            }
            maxi = max_element(frequencyArr);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
3/1/23, 3:32 PM - Vishal Verma: Hogya?

3/1/23, 3:32 PM - Vishal Verma: soln. me kiya hoga kisi ne

3/9/23, 10:43 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
	int t = 1;
	// cin>>t;
	while(t--)
	{
        int n = 4;
        // cin>>n;
        vector<int> permutation;
        for(int i=1 ; i<=n ; i++)
            permutation.push_back(i);
        
        int i = 1;
        int j;
        bool flag = true;
        
        while(i<n)
        {
            int sum = accumulate(permutation.begin(),permutation.begin()+i+1,0);
            cout<<"outer while sum="<<sum<<"i="<<i<<endl;
            
            if((sum % i+1) == 0)
            {
                j = i+1;
                while((sum % i+1) == 0)
                {
                    if(j>=n)
                    {
                        flag = false;
                        i==n;
                        break;
                    }
                    else
                    {
                        swap(permutation[i] , permutation[j]);
                        sum = sum - permutation[j] + permutation[i];
                        cout<<"Inner while sum="<<sum<<"j="<<j<<endl;
                        j++;
                    }
                }
            }
            
            else
            {
                i++;
            }
        }
        
        if(flag)
        {
            for(i=0 ; i<n ; i++)
            {
                cout<<permutation[i]<<" ";
            }
            cout<<endl;
        }
        
        else
            cout<<-1<<endl;
        
	}
	
	return 0;
}

3/9/23, 11:07 PM - Harshil B: #include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
	int turn;
	cin>>turn;
	while(turn--){
	    int len;cin>>len;
	    if(len & 1) cout<< -1 <<endl;
	    else{
	        int odd = 1,even = 4;
	        cout<<2<<" ";
	        for(int i=1;i<len;i++){
	            if(i & 1){
	                cout<<odd<<" ";
	                odd += 2;
	            }
	            else{
	             cout<<even<<" ";
	             even += 2;
	            }
	        }cout<<endl;
	    }
	}
	return 0;
}

3/19/23, 1:17 PM - Harshil B: Khudse kra tha?

3/19/23, 1:19 PM - Vishal Verma: Hn map use kra tha
3/19/23, 1:20 PM - Vishal Verma: Hr level k correspond node ko vector me dalta gya
3/19/23, 1:20 PM - Vishal Verma: For upr wale level pr node se link kra diya
3/19/23, 1:22 PM - Harshil B: Pr usme ye kaise pta chlega
Ki ek dash jo h
Vo root node ke liye h
Ya kisi aur child node ka child h
3/19/23, 1:24 PM - Vishal Verma: You deleted this message
3/19/23, 1:24 PM - Vishal Verma: /**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * struct TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode *left;
 *     TreeNode *right;
 *     TreeNode() : val(0), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
 *     TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
 *     TreeNode(int x, TreeNode *left, TreeNode *right) : val(x), left(left), right(right) {}
 * };
 */
class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* recoverFromPreorder(string traversal) {
        unordered_map<int , vector<TreeNode*>> mp;
        string rootVal = "";

        // processing for the root node
        int start = 0;
        while(start<traversal.size() && traversal[start] != '-'){
            rootVal += traversal[start];
            start++;
        }

        // pushing the root node as value of key level 0
        TreeNode *root = new TreeNode(stoi(rootVal));
        mp[0].push_back(root);

        for(int i=start ; i<traversal.size() ; i++){
            int level = 0;
            string num = "";
            int val;

            // finding the level of the node
            while(i < traversal.size() && traversal[i] == '-'){
                level++;
                i++;
            }

            // finding the value of the node
            while(i < traversal.size() && traversal[i] != '-'){
                num += traversal[i];
                i++;
            }
            val = stoi(num);
            i--;

            // creating a new node with value derived as "val"
            TreeNode *temp = new TreeNode(val);
            mp[level].push_back(temp);     

            // linking the curr node with the last node of previous level in the map
            // if left is empty then link the curr to left of parent root
            if(mp[level-1].back()->left == NULL)
                mp[level-1].back()->left = temp;
            // if right is empty then link the curr to right of parent root
            else
                mp[level-1].back()->right = temp;

        }
        return root;
    }
};
3/19/23, 1:26 PM - Vishal Verma: Hr level k liye mene vector bna liya 
Ab curr node ka level nikal lio dash count krk
3/19/23, 1:26 PM - Vishal Verma: Or uska parent node whi hoga jo level-1 wale vector me last node hoga

3/19/23, 9:27 PM - Harshil B: #include<bits/stdc++.h>
#include<unordered_map>
using namespace std;


int main(){
    int turn;
    cin>>turn;
    while(turn--){
        int len;
        cin>>len;

        string s;
        cin>>s;

        bool flag = false;

        unordered_map<char,int>freq;
        for(int i=1;i<len;i++){
            //two adjacent characters shouldn't be same
            if(s[i] == s[i-1]){
                flag = true;
                // cout<<"NO"<<endl;
                break;
            }
            else{
                if(freq.find(s[i])!=freq.end()){
                    freq[s[i]] = abs(i - (freq[s[i]]));
                    if(freq[s[i]] & 1){
                        flag = true;
                        // cout<<"NO"<<endl;
                        break;
                    }
                }
                else{
                    freq[s[i]] = i;
                }
            }
        }
        if(flag == false) cout<<"YES"<<endl;
        else cout<<"NO"<<endl;
    }
    return 0;
}

3/19/23, 9:29 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void solution(){
    int n;
    string str;

    cin>>n;
    cin>>str;

    map<char,int> mp;
    stack<char> st;
    bool flag = true;
    
    for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
        char ch = str[i];
        if(st.empty())
        {
            st.push(ch);
            mp[ch] = i;
        }

        else if(st.top() == ch || ((mp.find(ch) != mp.end()) && ((i - mp[ch])%2 != 0)))
        {
            flag = false;
            break;
        }

        else
        {
            st.push(ch);
            mp[ch] = i;
        }
    }

    if(flag)
        cout<<"YES"<<endl;
    else    
        cout<<"NO"<<endl;

}

int main()
{
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    while (t--)
    {
        solution();
    }
    
    return 0;
}

3/19/23, 9:50 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void solution(){
    int n , q;
    cin>>n>>q;

    vector<int> arr(n);
    long long sum = 0;
    for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
        cin>>arr[i];
        sum += arr[i];
    }

    int l , r , k;
    while (q--)
    {
        long long tempSum = sum;
        cin>>l>>r>>k;

        for(int i=l-1 ; i<r ; i++){
            tempSum -= arr[i];
            tempSum += k;
        }

        if(tempSum%2 == 1)
            cout<<"YES"<<endl;
        else
            cout<<"NO"<<endl;
    }
    
}

int main()
{
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    while (t--)
    {
        solution();
    }
    
    return 0;
}

3/19/23, 10:05 PM - Harshil B: #include<bits/stdc++.h>
#include<unordered_map>
using namespace std;


int main(){
    int turn;
    cin>>turn;
    while(turn--){
        int len,quer;
        cin>>len>>quer;
        vector<int>arr(len),pre(len,0);
        int sum = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<len;i++){
            cin>>arr[i];
            sum+=arr[i];
        }
        pre[0] = arr[0];

        for(int i=1;i<len;i++){
            pre[i] = arr[i] + pre[i-1];
        }

        while(quer--){
            int left,right,k;
            cin>>left>>right>>k;
            int toSubt = pre[right-1] - (pre[left-1] - arr[left-1]);

            int newSum = sum - toSubt + (right-left+1)*k;

            if(newSum&1) cout<<"YES"<<endl;

            else cout<<"NO"<<endl;
        }
    }
    return 0;
}

3/23/23, 10:20 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <iostream>
#include <ctime>
using namespace std;

int linearSearch(int *arr , int size , int key){
    for(int i=0 ; i<size ; i++){
        if(arr[i] == key)
            return i;
    }
    return -1;
}


int main()
{
    int arr[100000];
    int key;
    int size;
    struct timespec start;
    struct timespec stop;

    cout<<"Enter size of the array : ";
    cin>>size;

    for(int i=0 ; i<size ; i++){
        arr[i] = rand()%100;
    }

    cout<<"Enter key element to search for : ";
    cin>>key;

    // Start the timer
    clock_t start = clock();
    int res = linearSearch(arr , size , key);
    // Stop the timer and calculate the elapsed time
    clock_t stop = clock();
    double duration = static_cast<double>(stop-start) / CLOCKS_PER_SEC;


    if(res == -1)
        cout<<"Not Found"<<endl;
    else
        cout<<"Found at index "<<res<<endl;

    // Print the elapsed time in seconds
    std::cout << "Time taken: " << duration << " s" << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

3/25/23, 2:00 PM - Vishal Verma: class Solution {
public:
    string originalDigits(string s) {
        unordered_map<char,int> mp;
        string ans;

        for(char ch : s){
            mp[ch]++;
        }

        // processing for "0" with unique character 'z'
        if(mp.find('z') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['z'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['z']--;
                mp['e']--;
                mp['r']--;
                mp['o']--;
                ans.push_back('0');
            }
        }
        // processing for "6" with unique character 'x'
        if(mp.find('x') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['x'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['s']--;
                mp['i']--;
                mp['x']--;
                ans.push_back('6');
            }
        }
        // processing for "8" with unique character 'g'
        if(mp.find('g') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['g'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['e']--;
                mp['i']--;
                mp['g']--;
                mp['h']--;
                mp['t']--;
                ans.push_back('8');
            }
        }
        // processing for "2" with unique character 'w'
        if(mp.find('w') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['w'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['t']--;
                mp['w']--;
                mp['o']--;
                ans.push_back('2');
            }
        }
        // processing for "4" with unique character 'u'
        if(mp.find('u') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['u'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['f']--;
                mp['o']--;
                mp['u']--;
                mp['r']--;
                ans.push_back('4');
            }
        }
        // only "4" and "5" have character 'f' we  have already processed "4"
        // Now its turn for "5"
        if(mp.find('f') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['f'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['f']--;
                mp['i']--;
                mp['v']--;
                mp['e']--;
                ans.push_back('5');
            }
        }
        // only "6" and "7" have character 's' we  have already processed "6"
        // Now its turn for "7"     
        if(mp.find('s') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['s'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['s']--;
                mp['e']--;
                mp['v']--;
                mp['e']--;
                mp['n']--;
                ans.push_back('7');
            }
        }
        // only "2" and "1" have character 'o' we  have already processed "2"
        // Now its turn for "1"
        if(mp.find('o') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['o'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['o']--;
                mp['n']--;
                mp['e']--;
                ans.push_back('1');
            }
        }
        // only "3" and "8" have character 'h' we  have already processed "8"
        // Now its turn for "3"
        if(mp.find('h') != mp.end()){
            int num = mp['h'];
            for(int i=0 ; i<num ; i++){
                mp['t']--;
                mp['h']--;
                mp['r']--;
                mp['e']--;
                mp['e']--;
                ans.push_back('3');
            }
        }
        // only "5" , "6" , "8" and "9" have character 'i' we  have already processed "5","6","8"
        // Now its turn for "9"
        if(mp.find('i')!=mp.end()){
            int num=mp['i'];
            for(int i = 0;i<num;i++){
                mp['n']--;
                mp['i']--;
                mp['n']--;
                mp['e']--;
                ans+=('9');
            }
        }

        sort(ans.begin(),ans.end());
        return ans;
    }
};

3/27/23, 8:34 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void heapify(vector<int>&arr, int N, int i)
{
    int largest = i;
 
    int left = 2 * i + 1;
 
    int right = 2 * i + 2;

    if (left < N && arr[left] > arr[largest])
 
        largest = left;
 
    if (right < N && arr[right] > arr[largest])
 
        largest = right;
 
    if (largest != i) {
        swap(arr[i], arr[largest]);
        heapify(arr, N, largest);
    }
}

void heapSort(vector<int>&arr, int N)
{
     for (int i = N - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        swap(arr[0], arr[i]);
        heapify(arr, i, 0);
    }
}


void display(vector<int> arr , int size)
{
    for (int i = 0; i < size ; i++)
    {
        cout << arr[i] << " ";
    }
}

int main()
{
    vector<int> A(100000);
    int n;
    cout<<endl<<"Enter size of the array between 1 to 100000 : ";
    cin>>n;
    
    for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
        A[i] = rand()%1000;
    }

    
    // Start the timer
    clock_t startTime = clock();
    heapSort(A, n);

    cout << endl << "Array after After Sorting..." << endl;
    display(A, n);
    
    clock_t endTime = clock();
    cout<<fixed;cout<<setprecision(11);
    cout <<endl << endl<<"Time Taken : " << (double)(endTime-startTime)/CLOCKS_PER_SEC << " seconds" << endl;
    
    return 0;
}

3/30/23, 7:46 PM - Harshil B: Insertion sort in linked list vala vector ke alawa kisi aur approach se kiya hai?
3/30/23, 8:26 PM - Vishal Verma: You deleted this message
3/30/23, 8:27 PM - Vishal Verma: Hn
3/30/23, 8:28 PM - Vishal Verma: You deleted this message
3/30/23, 8:28 PM - Vishal Verma: Fir normal insertion sort wala logic lga de list end
3/30/23, 8:29 PM - Vishal Verma: Fir decreasing order me sort ho jaegi
3/30/23, 8:29 PM - Vishal Verma: Usko reverse krk bhej
3/30/23, 8:43 PM - Harshil B: List end se iteration kaise hogi
Pointer thodi h koi
3/30/23, 8:44 PM - Vishal Verma: recursively
3/30/23, 8:44 PM - Vishal Verma: /**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * struct ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode *next;
 *     ListNode() : val(0), next(nullptr) {}
 *     ListNode(int x) : val(x), next(nullptr) {}
 *     ListNode(int x, ListNode *next) : val(x), next(next) {}
 * };
 */
class Solution {
public:

    ListNode *reverse(ListNode *head){
        if(head == NULL)
            return NULL;
        
        ListNode *curr = head;
        ListNode *prev = NULL;
        ListNode *next;
        while(curr){
            next = curr->next;
            curr->next = prev;
            prev = curr;
            curr = next;
        }
        return prev;
    }

    ListNode *sort(ListNode *curr){
        if(curr == NULL)
            return NULL;

        // recursive call
        curr->next = sort(curr->next);

        ListNode *next = curr->next;
        ListNode *prev = curr;
        int temp = curr->val;
        
        while(next && temp < next->val){
            prev->val = next->val;
            prev = next;
            next = next->next;
        }
        
        prev->val = temp;
        return curr;
    }

    ListNode* insertionSortList(ListNode* head) {
        
        ListNode *curr = head;
        // calling the custom sort function
        curr = sort(curr);

        // reversing the list because we got the list in decreasing order after sorting
        curr = reverse(curr);
        return curr;
    }
};

4/12/23, 7:55 PM - Harshil B: string simplifyPath(string s) {
        stack<string>st;
        int n = s.size();

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(s[i] == '/') continue;
            string temp;

            while(i < n && s[i] != '/')
            {
                temp += s[i];
                i++;
            }

            if(temp == ".") continue;
            else if(temp == ".."){
                if(!st.empty()) st.pop();
            }
            else{
                st.push(temp);
            }
        }

        if(st.empty()) return "/";

        string ans = "";
        // worst case -> O(n)
        while(!st.empty()){
            ans = "/" + st.top() + ans;
            st.pop();
        }
        return ans;
    }
4/12/23, 7:55 PM - Vishal Verma: O(N)

4/17/23, 11:41 PM - Harshil B: long RootFinder::Bisection(tInterval A){
    if (I.isZero())
        throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Zero interval for search.\n");
    if (!I.isInitialized())
        throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Interval not initialized for search.\n");
    if (t == POLYNOMIAL && Poly.isZero()) throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Polynomial not initialized.\n");
    if (t == FUNCTION && Func.isZero()) throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Function not initialized.\n");
    double a = A.x;
    double b = A.y;
    double c = 0;
    double eps = 1e-9; // set the desired precision

    while (b - a > eps) {
        c = (a + b) / 2;
        if (Func(c) == 0) {
            break;
        } else if (Func(a) * Func(c) < 0) {
            b = c;
        } else {
            a = c;
        }
    }
    return c;
    // return -1; //dummy value
}
4/18/23, 12:03 AM - Vishal Verma: <Media omitted>
4/18/23, 12:09 AM - Harshil B: long RootFinder::Bisection(tInterval A){
    if (I.isZero())
        throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Zero interval for search.\n");
    if (!I.isInitialized())
        throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Interval not initialized for search.\n");
    if (t == POLYNOMIAL && Poly.isZero()) throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Polynomial not initialized.\n");
    if (t == FUNCTION && Func.isZero()) throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Function not initialized.\n");
    double a = A.x;
    double b = A.y;
    double c = (a + b) / 2;
    double eps = 1e-9;  // Desired accuracy of root

    if (Fn(a) * Fn(b) >= 0) {
        // cout << "Error: f(a) and f(b) have same sign" << endl;
        return NAN;
    }

    while ((b - a) >= eps) {
        // Check if root lies between a and c
        if (Fn(a) * Fn(c) < 0) {
            b = c;  // Set b to c
        } else {
            a = c;  // Set a to c
        }

        // Calculate new midpoint
        c = (a + b) / 2;
    }

    return c;  // Return root
}
4/18/23, 12:38 AM - Harshil B: long RootFinder::Bisection(tInterval A){
    if (I.isZero())
        throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Zero interval for search.\n");
    if (!I.isInitialized())
        throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Interval not initialized for search.\n");
    if (t == POLYNOMIAL && Poly.isZero()) throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Polynomial not initialized.\n");
    if (t == FUNCTION && Func.isZero()) throw myException("Error:- BisectionSearch: Function not initialized.\n");
    
    double fa,fb,fc,c,fd;
    int n = 1;
    double tol = 0.001;
    fa = Fn(A.x);
    fb = Fn(A.y);
    if(abs(fa) < tol){
        return (A.x);
    }
    if(abs(fb)<tol){
        return(A.y);
    }
    while(n<eps){
        c = A.x+(A.y-A.x)/2.0;
        fc = Fn(c);
        if(abs(fc) < (tol*tol) || (A.y-A.x) < tol) return c;
        n++;
        if(SIGN(fc) == SIGN(fa)){
            A.x = c; fa = fc;
        }
        else{
            A.y = c;fb = fc;
        }
    }
    return c;
}

5/3/23, 6:56 PM - Vishal Verma: class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> findDifference(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans(2);

        sort(nums1.begin()  , nums1.end());
        sort(nums2.begin()  , nums2.end());

        int i=0;
        int curr = nums1[0];
        while(i < nums1.size()){
            while(i<nums1.size() && curr == nums1[i])
                i++;    
            
            if(!binary_search(nums2.begin() , nums2.end() , curr))
                ans[0].push_back(curr);

            if(i < nums1.size())
                curr = nums1[i];
        }

        i=0;
        curr = nums2[0];
        while(i < nums2.size()){
            while(i<nums2.size() && curr == nums2[i])
                i++;    
            
            if(!binary_search(nums1.begin() , nums1.end() , curr))
                ans[1].push_back(curr);

            if(i < nums2.size())
                curr = nums2[i];
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

5/5/23, 9:29 PM - Vishal Verma: class Solution {
public:

    bool isVowel(char ch){
        return ch=='a'||ch=='e'||ch=='i'||ch=='o'||ch=='u';
    }

    int maxVowels(string s, int k) {
        int maxVowels = 0;

        for(int i=0 ; i<k && i<s.length() ; i++){
            if(isVowel(s[i])){
                maxVowels++;
            }
        }

        int i=0;
        int j=k;
        int count = maxVowels;
        while(j<s.length()){

            if(isVowel(s[i++])){
                count--;
            }

            if(isVowel(s[j++])){
                count++;
            }

            maxVowels = max(maxVowels , count);
        }

        return maxVowels;
    }
};
5/5/23, 9:29 PM - Vishal Verma: kuch alg kiya h tune?
5/5/23, 9:30 PM - Harshil B: int maxVowels(string s, int k) {
        unordered_set<char> vowels = {'a', 'e', 'i', 'o', 'u'};
        int max_count = 0;
        int count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
            if (i >= k && vowels.count(s[i-k])) {
                count--;
            }
            if (vowels.count(s[i])) {
                count++;
            }
            max_count = max(max_count, count);
        }
        return max_count;
    }

5/7/23, 12:28 AM - Vishal Verma: The application layer is the topmost layer of the OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model, and it is responsible for providing network services and protocols to applications running on the network. The application layer defines how applications interact with the network, and it provides a set of standardized protocols and services for this purpose.

Here are the steps to understand the application layer in computer networks:

Definition: The application layer provides a way for applications to communicate with each other over a network. It provides a set of protocols that define the rules for how data is transmitted and received between applications. Examples of application layer protocols include HTTP, FTP, SMTP, and DNS.

Functionality: The application layer provides several key functions, including data encryption, data compression, error detection and correction, and network management. For example, the HTTPS protocol provides secure transmission of data over the internet, while the DNS protocol is responsible for resolving domain names to IP addresses.

Applications: The application layer supports a wide variety of applications, including web browsers, email clients, instant messaging programs, and file transfer programs. These applications use different protocols to communicate with other applications on the network
5/7/23, 12:28 AM - Vishal Verma: HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol) is a protocol used for transmitting data over the internet. It is primarily used for the transfer of web pages and other content from web servers to web browsers. When you enter a website's URL into your browser, your browser sends an HTTP request to the web server, which then responds with the requested web page.

FTP (File Transfer Protocol) is a protocol used for transferring files over a network. It is often used for uploading and downloading files from a remote server, such as a web server. FTP uses a client-server architecture, where the client sends commands to the server to initiate and manage file transfers.

SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol) is a protocol used for sending and receiving email over the internet. It is responsible for the transfer of email messages from the sender's email client to the recipient's email server. SMTP is also used for transferring email messages between email servers.

DNS (Domain Name System) is a protocol used for resolving domain names to IP addresses. When you enter a domain name into your browser, your computer sends a DNS request to a DNS server, which then responds with the IP address of the web server associated with that domain name. This allows your browser to connect to the web server and retrieve the requested web page.

Overall, these protocols play a crucial role in enabling communication and data transfer over computer networks. HTTP is used for web browsing, FTP for file transfers, SMTP for email communication, and DNS for resolving domain names to IP addresses. Each protocol has its own unique features and functionalities, and together they make it possible for us to communicate, share data, and access information over the internet.

5/7/23, 10:22 PM - Harshil B: n the Bresenham's circle algorithm, the decision parameter d is used to determine which pixel to plot at each step of the circle drawing process. The value of d is calculated based on the distance between the current pixel and the ideal circle.

When d is equal to zero, the algorithm has two possible choices for the next pixel to plot, because there are two pixels that are equidistant from the ideal circle. In this case, the algorithm chooses one of the two pixels based on a predetermined rule (such as choosing the pixel with the smaller x-coordinate).

To prove that the two pixels are not at equal distance to the circle, let's consider the specific case where d is equal to zero, and let's assume that the algorithm chooses the pixel with the smaller x-coordinate.

In this case, the two possible pixels are (x + 1, y) and (x + 1, y - 1), where (x, y) is the current pixel being plotted. Both of these pixels are on the same vertical line, and they have the same x-coordinate, which means that they are at the same distance from the y-axis.

However, they are not at the same distance from the ideal circle. If we draw a diagram of the circle and these two pixels, we can see that the pixel (x + 1, y) is slightly closer to the ideal circle than the pixel (x + 1, y - 1). This is because the ideal circle has a radius that is greater than 1, which means that as we move away from the center of the circle, the distance between the pixels and the ideal circle becomes greater.

Therefore, we can conclude that when d is equal to zero in the Bresenham's circle algorithm, the two possible pixels are not at equal distance to the ideal circle. The algorithm chooses one of these pixels based on a predetermined rule, but neither of them is exactly on the ideal circle.

Example se solve krke dikhaya hai
5/7/23, 10:32 PM - Harshil B: To prove that both pixels are not at equal distance to the circle when the decision parameter d is equal to 0 in the Bresenham's circle algorithm, we can use an example with a circle of radius 5 centered at the origin.

Here are the steps of the algorithm for the first quadrant of the circle (i.e., x >= y):

vbnet
Copy code
Step 1: Set the initial point to (0, r) = (0, 5) and compute the decision parameter d = 3 - 2r = -7.
Step 2: Plot the first pixel at (x, y) = (0, 5).
Step 3: Compute the next point and the new decision parameter:
       if d < 0, the next point is (x+1, y) = (1, 5) and d = d + 4x + 6 = -3
       if d >= 0, the next point is (x+1, y-1) = (1, 4) and d = d + 4(x-y) + 10 = 1
Step 4: Plot the next pixel at (x, y) = (1, 4).
Step 5: Repeat step 3 and 4 until x >= y.

At the point where `d` is equal to 0, we have:

Step 12: (4, 1)    d = 0
This means that the next point on the circle could either be (5, 1) or (4, 0), depending on the sign of d.

If d is negative, the next point will be (5, 1), and if d is non-negative, the next point will be (4, 0).

Let's calculate the distances from these points to the center of the circle:

Distance from (5, 1) to the origin:

scss
Copy code
d = sqrt((5-0)^2 + (1-0)^2) = sqrt(26) ≈ 5.1
Distance from (4, 0) to the origin:

scss
Copy code
d = sqrt((4-0)^2 + (0-0)^2) = 4
As we can see, these distances are not equal, which means that the two pixels are not at equal distance to the circle when d is equal to 0. Therefore, we have proved numerically that both pixels are not at equal distance to the circle when the decision parameter d is equal to 0 in the Bresenham's circle algorithm.

5/30/23, 7:04 PM - Vishal Verma: class Solution {
public:

    bool solve(vector<vector<char>>& board, string &word , int row , int col , int idx , int &n , int &m){
        // base case
        if(idx == word.length()){
            return true;    
        }
        
        if(row<0 || row==n || col<0 || col==m || board[row][col] == '0' || board[row][col] != word[idx]){
            return false;
        }
        
        board[row][col] = '0';
        
        // go up
        bool up = solve(board , word , row-1 , col , idx+1 , n , m);
        // go right
        bool right = solve(board , word , row , col+1 , idx+1 , n , m);
        // go down
        bool down = solve(board , word , row+1 , col , idx+1 , n , m);
        // go left
        bool left = solve(board , word , row , col-1 , idx+1 , n , m);
        
        return up || right || down || left;
    }

    bool isWordExist(vector<vector<char>>& board, string word) {
        int n = board.size();
        int m = board[0].size();
        
        for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
            for(int j=0 ; j<m ; j++){
                if(board[i][j] == word[0]){
                    bool res = solve(board , word , i , j , 0 , n , m);
                    if(res == true)
                        return true;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
5/30/23, 7:05 PM - Harshil B: dfs se kra h kya tunne
5/30/23, 7:08 PM - Harshil B: bool isValid(int nr,int nc,int n,int m){
        return nr<n && nr>=0 && nc<m && nc>=0;
    }
    bool isWordExist(vector<vector<char>>& board, string word) {
        // Code here
        int n = board.size();
        int m = board[0].size();
        queue<pair<int,int>>q;
        vector<vector<int>>vis(n,vector<int>(m,0));
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<m;j++){
                if(board[i][j] == word[0]){
                    q.push({i,j});
                    vis[i][j] = 1;
                }
            }
        }
        int delRow[] = {-1,0,1,0};
        int delCol[] = {0,1,0,-1};
        int ind = 1;
        while(!q.empty() && ind < word.size()){
            int r = q.front().first;
            int c = q.front().second;
            q.pop();
            for(int i=0;i<4;i++){
                int nr = r + delRow[i];
                int nc = c + delCol[i];
                if(isValid(nr,nc,n,m) && !vis[nr][nc] && board[nr][nc] == word[ind]){
                    q.push({nr,nc});
                    vis[nr][nc] = 1;
                    ind++;
                }
            }
            if(ind >= word.size()) return true;
        }
        
        return false;
    }

5/31/23, 10:24 PM - Vishal Verma: class UndergroundSystem {
public:

    // stores id as key and pair of(startStaion , startTime) as value
    unordered_map<int , pair<string,int>> checkInMap; 
    // stores startStation as key and map of(endStation,timeTaken) as value
    unordered_map<string , unordered_map<string,vector<int>>> timeMap;

    UndergroundSystem() {
        
    }
    
    void checkIn(int id, string stationName, int t) {
        checkInMap[id].first = stationName;
        checkInMap[id].second = t;
    }
    
    void checkOut(int id, string stationName, int t) {
        // fetch startStation from checkInMap for corresponding id
        string startStation = checkInMap[id].first;
        // fetch startTime from checkInMap for corresponding id
        int startTime = checkInMap[id].second;
        // find timeTaken to reach 
        int timeTaken = t - startTime;
        // Update time taken to reach from startStation to endStation in timeMap
        timeMap[startStation][stationName].push_back(timeTaken);
        // remove the entry of id from checkInMap since journey is over
        checkInMap.erase(id);
    }
    
    double getAverageTime(string startStation, string endStation) {
        double avg;
        // retrive vector which contains time taken by all the id's which travelled from
        // satrtStaion to endStation
        vector<int> times = timeMap[startStation][endStation];
        avg = (double)accumulate(times.begin() , times.end() , 0) / (double)times.size();
        return avg;
    }
};

6/4/23, 10:06 AM - Vishal Verma: class Solution {
public:
    long long matrixSumQueries(int n, vector<vector<int>>& queries) {
        vector<vector<int>> mat(n , vector<int>(n));
        unordered_map<int,int> row;
        unordered_map<int,int> col;
        unordered_map<int,int> rCount;
        unordered_map<int,int> cCount;
        int count = 1;
        long long ans = 0;
        
        for(auto i : queries){
            if(i[0] == 0){
                row[i[1]] = i[2];
                rCount[i[1]] = count;
            }
            else{
                col[i[1]] = i[2];
                cCount[i[1]] = count;
            }
            count++;
        }
        
        for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
            for(int j=0 ; j<n ; j++){
                if(rCount[i] >= cCount[j]){
                    mat[i][j] = row[i];
                }
                else{
                    mat[i][j] = col[j];
                }
                ans += mat[i][j];
            }
        }
        
        return ans;
    }
};

6/10/23, 2:55 AM - Vishal Verma: class Solution
{
    public:
        void Rearrange(int arr[], int n)
        {
            int i=0;
            int j=0;
            while(i<n && j<n){
                // find first occurence of -ve no.
                while(i<n && arr[i] >= 0)
                    i++;
                
                while(j<n && arr[j] < 0)
                    j++;
                
                if(i<n && j<n && j<i){
                    swap(arr[j] , arr[i]);
                }
                else{
                    i++;
                }
                
            }
        }
};

6/10/23, 3:00 AM - Vishal Verma: private static void rearrangeArr(int[] arr, int n) {

        for(int i=0;i<arr.length;i++){

            if(arr[i]<0){

                int nextPositive;

                nextPositive = findNextPositive(arr,i,n);

                if(nextPositive == -1){

                    break;

                }else{

                    rotate(arr,i,nextPositive);

                }

            }

            if(arr[i]>=0){

                int nextNegative;

                nextNegative = findNextNegative(arr,i,n);

                if(nextNegative == -1){

                    break;

                }else{

                    rotate(arr,i,nextNegative);

                }

            }

        }

    }

 

    private static void rotate(int[] arr, int start, int end) {

        int temp = arr[end];

        for(int i = end-1;i>=start;i--){

            arr[i+1] = arr[i];

        }

        arr[start] = temp;

    }

    private static int findNextNegative(int[] arr, int i, int n) {

        for(int j=i;j<arr.length;j++){

            if(arr[j]<0){

                return j;

            }

        }

        return -1;

    }

    private static int findNextPositive(int[] arr, int i, int n) {

        for(int j=i;j<arr.length;j++){

            if(arr[j]>=0){

                return j;

            }

        }

        return -1;

    }

6/10/23, 3:02 AM - Vishal Verma: public void PushAndPut(long a[],int j,int i)

    {

        long temp = a[i];

        for(int k=i;k>j;k--)

        {      a[k] = a[k-1];

        }

       a[j] = temp;

    }  

    

    public void Rearrange(long a[], long n)

    {

        int j = -1;

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)

        {

            if(a[i]<0)

            {

                j++;

                PushAndPut(a,j,i);

            }

        }

    }

6/26/23, 7:30 PM - Harshil B: int monsterPaused(vector<int>&attack, int d) {
    int totalTime = 0;
    int prevTime = -1;

    for (int currTime : attack) {
        if (currTime > prevTime) {
            totalTime += d;
            prevTime = currTime + d - 1;
        } else {
            totalTime += currTime + d - 1 - prevTime;
            prevTime = currTime + d - 1;
        }
    }

    return totalTime;
}

6/26/23, 8:25 PM - Harshil B: int solve(ll k,vector<int>&arr){
    priority_queue<ll> pq;
    ll x;
    //max point pehle aaega -> greedy
    for(int i=0;i<arr.size();i++){
        pq.push(arr[i]);
    }

    ll dis=0;
    bool check = false;
    // traverse on priority queue
    while(!pq.empty()){
        x= pq.top();
        // baad ke k distances hatado
        for(int i=0;i<k;i++){
            pq.pop();
            if(pq.empty()) break;
        }

        if(check) dis+=x*2;
        else dis+=x;
        check = true;
    }

    return (dis*5);
}
6/26/23, 8:27 PM - Vishal Verma: isme indexes k hisaab se hoga
6/26/23, 8:27 PM - Harshil B: Krde jldi jo samajh arha h

6/26/23, 8:32 PM - Vishal Verma: int solve(ll k,vector<int>&arr){
    int n = arr.size();
    priority_queue<int,vector<int>,greater<int>> pq;
    for(int i=0 ; i<arr.size() ; i++){
        if(pq.size() < k){
            pq.push(arr[i]);
        }
        else if(pq.top() < arr[i]){
            pq.pop();
            pq.push(arr[i]);
        }
    }
}

7/4/23, 11:26 PM - Vishal Verma: class Solution {
public:
    int singleNumber(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int> bits(32);
        int num = 0;
        
        for(int i : nums){
            int pos = 0;
            while(i){
                int rem = i%2;
                i = i>>1;
                if(rem == 1){
                    bits[pos]++;
                }
                pos++;
            }
        }

        for(int i=0 ; i<32 ; i++){
            if(bits[i]%3 == 1){
                num += pow(2,i);
            }
        }

        return num;
    }
};

7/5/23, 9:43 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#define ll long long

ll comb3(int n){
    ll ans = n*(n-1)*(n-2) / 6;
    return ans;
}
ll comb2(int n){
    ll ans = n*(n-1)*(n-2) / 2;
    return ans;
}

void solution(){
    int n,q;
    cin>>n>>q;
    priority_queue<int , vector<int> , greater<int>> pq;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        int x;
        cin>>x;
        pq.push(x);
    }

    // process till nC3

    ll maxK = comb3(n);
    // cout<<"maxK "<<maxK<<endl;
    vector<int> kValues(maxK);
    int i=0;
    while(i<maxK && !pq.empty()){
        int val = pq.top();
        ll pos = comb2(pq.size()-1);
        pq.pop();
        while(i<maxK && i<=pos){
            kValues[i++] = val; 
        }
    }
    
    for (int j = 0; j < q; j++)
    {
        int k;
        cin>>k;
        cout<<kValues[k]<<endl;
    }
    
}
 
int main()
{
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    while (t--)
    {
        solution();
    }
    
    return 0;
}

7/7/23, 8:49 PM - Harshil B: #include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void solve(string r1,string r2,string r3){
    //checking each row
    for(int i=0;i<3;i++){
        if((r1[i] == r2[i]) && r1[i] == r3[i]){
            char ch = r1[i];
            if(ch == '.'){
                cout<<"DRAW"<<endl;
                return;
            }
            else{
                cout<<ch<<endl;
            }
        }
    }

    //checking each column
    if((r1[0] == r1[1]) && (r1[0] == r1[2])){
            char ch = r1[0];
            if(ch == '.'){
                cout<<"DRAW"<<endl;
                return;
            }
            else{
                cout<<ch<<endl;
            }
    }
    if((r2[0] == r2[1]) && (r2[0] == r2[2])){
        char ch = r2[0];
            if(ch == '.'){
                cout<<"DRAW"<<endl;
                return;
            }
            else{
                cout<<ch<<endl;
            }
    }
    if((r3[0] == r3[1]) && (r3[0] == r3[2])){
        char ch = r3[0];
            if(ch == '.'){
                cout<<"DRAW"<<endl;
                return;
            }
            else{
                cout<<ch<<endl;
            }
    }

    //checking diagonals
    if(r1[0] == r2[1] && r1[0] == r3[2]){
        char ch = r1[0];
            if(ch == '.'){
                cout<<"DRAW"<<endl;
                return;
            }
            else{
                cout<<ch<<endl;
            }
    }
    if(r1[3] == r2[1] && r1[3] == r3[0]){
        char ch = r3[0];
            if(ch == '.'){
                cout<<"DRAW"<<endl;
                return;
            }
            else{
                cout<<ch<<endl;
            }
    }
}

int main(){
    int turn;
    cin>>turn;
    while(turn--){
        string r1,r2,r3;
        cin>>r1>>r2>>r3;

        solve(r1,r2,r3);
    }
    return 0;
}

7/7/23, 8:50 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void solution(){
    vector<vector<char>> g(3 , vector<char>(3));
    unordered_map<char , bool> mp;
    mp['X'] = true;
    mp['O'] = true;
    mp['+'] = true;
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++)
    {
        for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++)
        {
            cin>>g[i][j];
        }
    }

    // check all rows
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++)
    {
        if(g[i][0]==g[i][1] && g[i][1]==g[i][2] && mp[g[i][0]]){
            cout<<g[i][0]<<endl;
            return;
        }
    }

    // for all columns
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++)
    {
        if(g[0][i]==g[1][i] && g[1][i]==g[2][i] && mp[g[0][i]]){
            cout<<g[0][i]<<endl;
            return;
        }
    }
    
    // check diagonal
    if(g[0][0]==g[1][1] && g[1][1]==g[2][2] && mp[g[0][0]]){
        cout<<g[0][0]<<endl;
        return;
    }

    if(g[0][2]==g[1][1] && g[1][1]==g[2][0] && mp[g[0][2]]){
        cout<<g[1][1]<<endl;
        return;
    }
    cout<<"DRAW"<<endl;
}

int main()
{
    int t;
    
    cin>>t;
    while (t--)
    {
        solution();
    }
    
    return 0;
}

7/7/23, 10:10 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

static bool cmp(pair<int,pair<int,int>> a , pair<int,pair<int,int>> b){
    if(a.first > b.first){
        return true;
    }

    else if(a.first == b.first){
        if(a.second.first < b.second.first){
            return true;
        }
        
        else{
            return false;
        }
    }
    else{
        return false;
    }
}

void solution(){
    int n , m , h ;
    cin>>n>>m>>h;
    vector<priority_queue<int,vector<int>,greater<int>>> vpq(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        for (int j = 0; j < m ; j++)
        {
            int a;
            cin>>a;
            vpq[i].push(a);
        }
    }
    
    vector<pair<int,pair<int,int>>> vp;

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        int pen = 0 , tt = 0 , po = 0;

        while(!vpq[i].empty()){
            int t = vpq[i].top();
            vpq[i].pop();
            if(tt + t <= h){
                pen += tt+t;
                tt += t;
                po++;
            }
        }
        // cout<<i<<": "<<po<<" "<<pen<<endl;
        vp.push_back({po , {pen , i}});
    }
        
    // cout<<endl;
    sort(vp.begin() , vp.end() , cmp);

    for(int i=0 ; i<n ; i++){
        auto p = vp[i];
        // cout<<p.second.second<<" "<<p.first<<" "<<p.second.first<<endl;
        if(p.second.second == 0){
            int res = i+1;
            // cout<<"res"<<res<<endl;
            i--;
            while(i>=0 && vp[i].first==p.first && vp[i].second.first==p.second.first){
                res--;
                i--;
            }
            cout<<res<<endl;
            return;
        }
    }
    // cout<<endl;
}

int main()
{
    int t;
    
    cin>>t;
    while (t--)
    {
        solution();
    }
    
    return 0;
}

7/25/23, 8:26 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void solution(){
    int n,m,k,H;
    cin>>n>>m>>k>>H;
    vector<int> hh(n);

    int ans = 0;
    int min = k;
    int max = (k*m)-k;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        cin>>hh[i];
        int dist = abs(H - hh[i]);
        if(dist%k == 0 && dist<=max){
            ans++;
        }
    }

    if(m == 1){
        cout<<0<<endl;
    }
    else{
        cout<<ans<<endl;
    }
    
}

int main()
{
    int t;
    
    cin>>t;
    while (t--)
    {
        solution();
    }
    
    return 0;
}

7/30/23, 7:44 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void countsort(vector<int>& arr, int exp)
{

    vector<int> farr(10, 0);

    // Creating frequency array

    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++)
    {
        farr[(arr[i] / exp) % 10]++;
    }

    // Making prefix sum array

    for (int i = 1; i < farr.size(); i++)
    {
        farr[i] += farr[i - 1];
    }

    // Creating array for storing sorted elements
    vector<int> ans(arr.size());

    for (int i = arr.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--)
    {
        int val = (arr[i] / exp) % 10;
        int pos = farr[val];
        int idx = pos - 1;
        ans[idx] = arr[i];
        farr[val]--;
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++)
    {
        arr[i] = ans[i];
    }

}

void radixsort(vector<int>& arr)
{
    int max = *std::max_element(arr.begin(), arr.end());
    int exp = 1;
    while (exp <= max)
    {
        // Have to declare countsort() before using
        countsort(arr, exp);
        exp = exp * 10;
    }

}

void display(vector<int>& arr)
{
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++)
    {
        cout << arr[i] << " ";
    }

}

int main()
{
    vector<int> arr = { 213,97,718,123,37,443,982,64,375,683 };
    radixsort(arr);
    display(arr);

    return 0;
}

9/16/23, 1:56 PM - Vishal Verma: #include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;


int solve(int n , vector<int> A , vector<int> B , int m){
    // priority_queue<int , vector<int> , greater<int>> pq;
    vector<int> degree(n);
    unordered_map<int,unordered_set<int>> mp;
    for(int i=0 ; i<m ; i++){
        degree[A[i]]++;
        degree[B[i]]++;
        mp[A[i]].insert(B[i]);
        mp[B[i]].insert(A[i]);
    }
    
    unordered_set<int> s1 , s2;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        if(degree[i] < 2){
            s1.insert(i);
        }
        else{
            s2.insert(i);
        }
    }

    int cnt = 0;
    while (s1.size())
    {
        for(int i : s1){
            if(degree[i]){
                int v = *mp[i].begin();
                mp[i].erase(v);
                mp[v].erase(i);
                degree[v]--;
            }
        }
        s1.clear();

        for(int i : s2){
            if(degree[i] < 2){
                s1.insert(i);
                s2.erase(i);
            }
        }
        cnt++;
    }
    
    return cnt;
    
}

int main()
{

    int n , m;
    cin>>n>>m;
    vector<int> A(m) , B(m);
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++)
    {
        cin>>A[i]>>B[i];
    }
    
    cout<<solve(n , A , B , m);
    return 0;
}

9/16/23, 2:17 PM - Vishal Verma: #include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;


int solve(int n , vector<int> A , vector<int> B , int m){
    // priority_queue<int , vector<int> , greater<int>> pq;
    vector<int> degree(n);
    unordered_map<int,unordered_set<int>> mp;
    for(int i=0 ; i<m ; i++){
        degree[A[i]]++;
        degree[B[i]]++;
        mp[A[i]].insert(B[i]);
        mp[B[i]].insert(A[i]);
    }
    
    unordered_set<int> s1 , s2;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        if(degree[i] < 2){
            s1.insert(i);
        }
        else{
            s2.insert(i);
        }
    }

    int cnt = 0;
    while (s1.size())
    {
        for(int i : s1){
            // cout<<i<<" ";
            if(degree[i]){
                int v = *mp[i].begin();
                mp[i].erase(v);
                mp[v].erase(i);
                if(degree[v])
                    degree[v]--;
                degree[i]--;
                // cout<<v<<" "<<degree[v];
            }
            // cout<<endl;
            // s1.erase(i);
        }
        cout<<endl;
        s1.clear();

        for(int i : s2){
            // cout<<i<<" "<<degree[i]<<endl;
            if(degree[i] < 2){
                s1.insert(i);
                s2.erase(i);
            }
            // cout<<s2.size()<<" "<<s1.size()<<endl;
        }
        cnt++;
    }
    
    return cnt;
    
}

int main()
{

    int n , m;
    cin>>n>>m;
    vector<int> A(m) , B(m);
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++)
    {
        cin>>A[i]>>B[i];
    }
    
    cout<<solve(n , A , B , m);
    return 0;
}

9/16/23, 7:16 PM - Vishal Verma: int countAnalogousArrays(vector<int>& arr, int lower, int higher) { 
    int max = std::numeric_limits<int>::min();  
    int n = lower; 
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) { 
        int k = arr[i]; 
        int k1 = n - k; 

        if (k1 > higher || k1 < lower) { 
            return 0; 
        } 

        n = k1; 
        max = std::max(max, n); 
    } 

    max = higher - max + 1; 

    return max; 
}

9/28/23, 12:16 AM - Harshil B: Certainly! When creating a project presentation (PPT), it's essential to include a section on dependencies and potential show stoppers to demonstrate that you've considered risks and challenges. Here are some examples of what you can write in these sections:

**Dependencies:**

1. **External API Integration:** Our project relies on integrating with a third-party API for real-time data updates. Successful API integration is a critical dependency for our project's functionality.

2. **Regulatory Approval:** We are awaiting regulatory approval for the new product features we plan to launch. Our project timeline is dependent on receiving this approval by [specific date].

3. **Supplier Deliveries:** Our project involves incorporating new components from [Supplier Name]. Timely deliveries from the supplier are crucial to meet our production deadlines.

4. **Cross-Department Collaboration:** The success of our project depends on collaboration with the marketing and sales departments for product promotion. Clear communication and cooperation between teams are essential.

5. **Infrastructure Upgrade:** Our project requires an upgrade to the existing server infrastructure to accommodate increased user load. We are dependent on the IT department to complete this upgrade by [date].

**Show Stoppers:**

1. **Data Security Vulnerability:** We've identified a potential data security vulnerability that, if not addressed, could result in data breaches. This issue must be resolved immediately to prevent any security breaches.

2. **Resource Shortage:** We are currently facing a shortage of skilled developers, which is impacting the project's progress. We need to address this resource gap urgently to meet project milestones.

3. **Technical Compatibility Issue:** An unexpected compatibility issue has arisen with a key software component, causing system crashes. This issue is a showstopper as it hinders any further development until resolved.

4. **Budget Overrun:** Our project is at risk of exceeding the allocated budget due to unexpected expenses. We need to reassess the budget and find cost-effective solutions to prevent a budgetary showstopper.

5. **Legal Compliance:** Recent changes in legislation may impact our project's compliance. We must ensure that our project aligns with these new regulations to avoid legal complications that could halt progress.

Including these dependencies and potential show stoppers in your project presentation demonstrates your team's awareness of risks and your commitment to addressing them proactively. It also allows stakeholders to understand the challenges and mitigation strategies for your project.
9/28/23, 12:34 AM - Harshil B: Certainly, for a career path guidance project involving the creation of a machine learning model, here are some potential dependencies and show stoppers to consider:

**Dependencies:**

1. **Data Collection:** The project relies heavily on access to comprehensive and accurate data about careers, job markets, and educational pathways. Ensuring data availability and quality is a critical dependency.

2. **Data Labeling:** If your machine learning model requires labeled data for supervised learning, you'll need a team to annotate or label the data correctly. This process can be time-consuming and may require subject matter expertise.

3. **Infrastructure:** Dependence on suitable hardware, software, and cloud services for model training and deployment is common. Ensuring access to the necessary infrastructure is essential.

4. **Access to Experts:** If your project involves domain-specific knowledge, such as career counseling or education expertise, having access to experienced professionals in these fields can be crucial for model validation and improvement.

5. **Regulatory Compliance:** Depending on the region or jurisdiction, there may be legal and ethical considerations related to handling user data and providing career guidance. Compliance with these regulations is essential.

**Show Stoppers:**

1. **Data Privacy and Security:** A significant showstopper could be a data breach or failure to adequately protect user data. Ensuring robust data privacy and security measures is critical.

2. **Data Quality Issues:** If the data used for model training is incomplete, outdated, or biased, it can severely impact the accuracy and effectiveness of your guidance system.

3. **Ethical Concerns:** Misleading or biased career recommendations can lead to ethical issues. Ensuring that the machine learning model provides fair and unbiased guidance is vital.

4. **Resource Constraints:** A shortage of skilled data scientists, machine learning engineers, or domain experts can delay the development and deployment of the ML model.

5. **Model Performance:** If the ML model's accuracy, precision, or recall is not up to the required standard, it can impede the effectiveness of the career guidance system and require extensive retraining efforts.

6. **User Adoption and Feedback:** The success of your career guidance system depends on user adoption. If users do not find the system helpful or user feedback is negative, it can be a showstopper, requiring reevaluation and improvements in user experience.

7. **Regulatory Changes:** New regulations or legal requirements related to career guidance or data privacy can suddenly halt or disrupt the project.

It's essential to identify these dependencies and show stoppers early in the project planning phase and develop strategies to mitigate risks and challenges. Regular monitoring and adaptation to changing circumstances will also be crucial for the project's success.

10/2/23, 8:57 PM - Vishal Verma: This grammar is not left-factored because the production alternatives for non-terminal A do not share a common prefix that can be factored out. Left factoring involves identifying common prefixes in production rules for the same non-terminal and factoring them out to simplify the grammar.

In this grammar, the alternatives start with different prefixes ("b" and "bC" in the first alternative, and "b" and "bE" in the second alternative). Since there is no common prefix among these alternatives, there's no left factoring that can be applied in this case.

10/7/23, 11:38 PM - Vishal Verma: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
 

void solution(){
    int n;
    cin>>n;
    double ans;
    vector<int> X(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        cin>>X[i];
    }
    sort(X.begin() , X.end());

    double last = (double)(X[n-1] + X[n-2])/2;
    double first;
    if(n==5){
        double a = (double)(X[0]+X[1]+X[2])/3;
        double b = (double)(X[0]+X[1])/2;
        double c = (double)(X[n-1]+X[n-2])/2;
        double d = (double)(X[n-1]+X[n-2]+X[n-3])/3;
        ans = max(c-a , d-b);
    }
    else{
        first = (double)(X[0]+X[1])/2;
        ans = last-first;
    }
    // cout<<first<<" "<<last<<endl;
    cout<<ans<<endl;
}
 
signed main()
{
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(0);
    cin.tie(0);
    cout.tie(0);
#ifndef ONLINE_JUDGE
    freopen("input2.txt", "r", stdin);
    freopen("output2.txt", "w", stdout);
#endif
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    for (int i = 0; i < t; i++)
    {
        cout << "Case #" << i + 1 << ": ";
        solution();
    }

    return 0;
}

Problem Sequence: Arrange the problems in a sequential order, where the solution to a problem must be used as input for the next problem in the sequence. Ensure that the final problem leads to a clear conclusion to determine the winner.

Submission and Grading: Teams must submit their code for each problem through a designated platform or submission system. The solutions will be evaluated for correctness, efficiency, and adherence to coding standards.

Penalties: Impose penalties for late submissions or incorrect solutions. Penalties can include time extensions for the next problem or point deductions.

10/8/23, 3:14 PM - Harshil B: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
#define int long long
#define ld double

ld solve()
{
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    int x;
    vector<ld> v(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        cin >> v[i];
    }

    sort(v.begin(), v.end());
    ld mini, maxi;

    if (n == 5)
    {
        ld a, b, c, d;
        a = v[0] + (v[1] - v[0]) / 2;
        b = v[n - 1] - (v[n - 1] - v[n - 3]) / 2;
        c = v[0] + (v[2] - v[0]) / 2;
        d = v[n - 1] - (v[n - 1] - v[n - 2]) / 2;

        if (b - a >= d - c)
        {
            mini = a;
            maxi = b;
        }
        else
        {
            mini = c;
            maxi = d;
        }
    }
    else
    {

        mini = v[0] + (v[1] - v[0]) / 2;
        maxi = v[n - 1] - (v[n - 1] - v[n - 2]) / 2;
    }
    return maxi - mini;
}

signed main()
{
    ios_base::sync_with_stdio(0);
    cin.tie(0);
    cout.tie(0);
#ifndef ONLINE_JUDGE
    freopen("input1.txt", "r", stdin);
    freopen("output1.txt", "w", stdout);
#endif
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    for (int i = 0; i < t; i++)
    {
        cout << "Case #" << i + 1 << ": ";
        cout << solve() << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

10/30/23, 8:23 PM - Harshil B: #include<bits/stdc++.h>
#define int long long
using namespace std;

void solve(){
    int n;
    cin>>n;
    vector<int>arr(n);
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        cin>>arr[i];
    }
    int check = 1,m=0;
    while(check<=n){
        check *= 2;
        m++;
    }
    m--;

    for(int i=m+1;i<n;i++){
        for(int j=0;j<=m;j++){
            if(arr[j]>arr[i]){
                cout<<"NO"<<endl;
                return;
            }
        }
    }
    cout<<"YES"<<endl;
    return;
}

signed main(){
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    while(t--){
       solve();
    }
    return 0;
}

11/25/23, 7:13 PM - Harshil B: #include <iostream>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <vector>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<int> arr(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        cin >> arr[i];
    }

    unordered_map<int, int> freq;

    long long countPairs = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        for (int j = 1; j * j <= arr[i]; ++j) {
            if (arr[i] % j == 0) {
                countPairs += freq[j];
                if (j * j != arr[i]) {
                    countPairs += freq[arr[i] / j];
                }
            }
        }
        freq[arr[i]]++;
    }

    cout << countPairs << endl;

    return 0;
}

12/4/23, 9:36 PM - Vishal Verma: Institutions mentioned:

Small Industries Development Bank of India (SIDBI):

Details: SIDBI, established in 1990, is the principal financial institution aimed at fostering and supporting the growth of small-scale industries in India. It operates under the Department of Financial Services, Ministry of Finance. SIDBI provides various financial and non-financial services to small businesses, including term loans, working capital, and project finance. It also collaborates with other financial institutions and banks to extend credit facilities to small and medium enterprises (SMEs).
National Small Industries Corporation (NSIC):

Details: NSIC is a central government agency established in 1955. It operates under the Ministry of Micro, Small, and Medium Enterprises. NSIC focuses on promoting the competitiveness of small businesses by providing integrated support services encompassing marketing, technology, finance, and other critical areas. NSIC also facilitates the participation of SMEs in government purchases and exports.
State Financial Corporations (SFCs):

Details: State Financial Corporations are financial institutions established at the state level to cater to the financial needs of small and medium enterprises within the respective states. Each state in India has its own SFC. These corporations offer various financial products, including term loans, working capital, and assistance for the establishment and expansion of small businesses. SFCs play a vital role in supporting local entrepreneurship and industrial development.
District Industries Centers (DICs):

Details: District Industries Centers operate at the district level and are part of the state government's initiatives to promote small businesses. They serve as a one-stop resource for entrepreneurs, assisting them in project identification, obtaining necessary approvals, and accessing financial support. DICs play a pivotal role in implementing government policies at the grassroots level, fostering the development of micro and small enterprises in their respective districts.
Khadi and Village Industries Commission (KVIC):

Details: KVIC is a statutory body established in 1957 under the Ministry of Micro, Small, and Medium Enterprises. It is responsible for the development and promotion of khadi and village industries in rural areas. KVIC supports small businesses by providing financial assistance, training, and market promotion for products produced by artisans and small entrepreneurs. The commission's focus on rural industries contributes to employment generation and sustainable development in rural communities.
These institutions collectively contribute to the comprehensive support structure for small businesses in India, addressing their financial, technological, and promotional needs at various levels of governance. Entrepreneurs can benefit from these institutions by accessing financial resources, gaining market exposure, and receiving guidance for sustainable business growth.

As you are aware, a campaign on “Voice of Youth – Viksit Bharat@2047” has been launched by Hon’ble Prime Minister Shri Narendra Modi on 11th December, 2023. This campaign aims to engage youth with Viksit Bharat Campaign and get their idea about this goal.


To get students feedback, a platform ‘‘Viksitbharat2047.MyGoV.in’’ has been started on 11th December, 2023. All students of Higher Education Institution are expected to submit their feedback by 25th December, 2023. To review the progress of participation State wise, a meeting has been scheduled at 10.30 A.M. on 15th December, which will be chaired by Union Secretary (Higher Education). 
All universities are requested to provide a report by 4.00 pm today.

12/18/23, 9:51 PM - Vishal Verma: Data preprocessing is a crucial step in the data analysis and machine learning pipeline. It involves cleaning and transforming raw data into a format that is suitable for analysis or model training. Here are some common data preprocessing techniques:

1. **Handling Missing Data:**
   - Identify and handle missing data by either removing rows or columns with missing values or imputing the missing values with statistical measures (e.g., mean, median, or mode).

2. **Data Cleaning:**
   - Correct any errors or inconsistencies in the data, such as typos, duplicate records, or outliers.

3. **Handling Outliers:**
   - Identify and deal with outliers by either removing them or transforming them using methods such as winsorization.

4. **Data Transformation:**
   - Scale or normalize features to bring them to a similar scale. Common techniques include Min-Max scaling, Z-score normalization, or robust scaling.

5. **Encoding Categorical Variables:**
   - Convert categorical variables into numerical representations using techniques like one-hot encoding or label encoding.

6. **Feature Engineering:**
   - Create new features that might improve the performance of a model. This could involve combining existing features, creating interaction terms, or transforming variables.

7. **Data Discretization:**
   - Convert continuous data into discrete bins. This can be useful when dealing with certain types of algorithms or when the relationships are better captured in a categorical form.

8. **Handling Imbalanced Data:**
   - Address class imbalances in classification problems by oversampling the minority class, undersampling the majority class, or using techniques like SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique).

9. **Date and Time Formatting:**
   - If your dataset includes date and time information, parse and format it properly. Extract relevant features like day of the week, month, or year.

10. **Text Cleaning (NLP):**
    - For natural language processing tasks, clean and preprocess text data by removing stop words, stemming or lemmatization, and handling special characters or punctuation.

11. **Normalization of Text Data:**
    - Convert text data to lowercase and remove any unnecessary white spaces to ensure consistency.

12. **Handling Duplicates:**
    - Identify and remove duplicate records from the dataset.

13. **Feature Scaling:**
    - Standardize or normalize numerical features to ensure that they have similar scales, especially for algorithms that are sensitive to the scale of input features.

14. **Principal Component Analysis (PCA):**
    - Use PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset while retaining important information.

15. **Data Integration:**
    - Combine data from multiple sources into a single, unified dataset.

The specific preprocessing steps you choose will depend on the nature of your data, the problem you're trying to solve, and the requirements of the algorithms you plan to use. It's often an iterative process, and the effectiveness of different techniques should be evaluated based on the performance of your models.
12/18/23, 9:52 PM - Vishal Verma: The binomial distribution is a discrete probability distribution that describes the number of successes in a fixed number of independent Bernoulli trials, where each trial has only two possible outcomes: success or failure. In the context of machine learning, the binomial distribution is often relevant in situations where there are binary outcomes, such as classification problems.

Here are a few ways in which the binomial distribution is used in machine learning:

1. **Binary Classification:**
   - In binary classification problems, where the outcome variable has two possible classes (e.g., 0 or 1, true or false, positive or negative), the binomial distribution can be used to model the number of successes (e.g., correctly classified instances) in a fixed number of trials (e.g., total number of instances).

2. **Evaluation Metrics:**
   - Many evaluation metrics used in machine learning, such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score, can be expressed in terms of the elements of a confusion matrix. The confusion matrix is constructed based on the outcomes of binary classification, making it related to the binomial distribution.

3. **Hypothesis Testing:**
   - In some cases, machine learning models may be assessed using hypothesis tests, where the null hypothesis assumes that the model's performance is no better than random chance. The binomial distribution can be used to calculate p-values and assess the statistical significance of the observed performance.

4. **A/B Testing:**
   - A/B testing is a common technique in machine learning and data science to compare the performance of two versions of a model or a system. The binomial distribution can be used to model the distribution of successes (e.g., conversions) in each variant.

5. **Bootstrap Sampling:**
   - In machine learning, bootstrap sampling is a resampling technique used for estimating the sampling distribution of a statistic. The binomial distribution plays a role in generating bootstrap samples and estimating confidence intervals for model performance metrics.

6. **Cross-Validation:**
   - When performing k-fold cross-validation, the binomial distribution is implicitly involved in the process of splitting the dataset into folds and evaluating the model's performance on different subsets.

Understanding the binomial distribution and its properties is valuable for interpreting and analyzing the results of machine learning models, especially in scenarios involving binary outcomes and discrete trial-based evaluations. It provides a probabilistic framework for reasoning about the variability and uncertainty associated with the model's performance.
12/18/23, 9:52 PM - Vishal Verma: BINOMIAL
12/18/23, 9:53 PM - Vishal Verma: The Poisson distribution is a discrete probability distribution that describes the number of events that occur within a fixed interval of time or space. It is often used in machine learning for tasks where the outcome of interest is the count of events that happen independently and at a constant average rate.

Here are some scenarios in machine learning where the Poisson distribution is relevant:

1. **Text Mining and Natural Language Processing (NLP):**
   - In text mining, the Poisson distribution can be used to model the distribution of word occurrences in a document or a collection of documents. This is particularly useful when dealing with rare words.

2. **Web Analytics:**
   - Web events, such as the number of clicks, page views, or downloads, can be modeled using a Poisson distribution. This is beneficial for tasks like predicting the number of clicks on an advertisement or the number of visits to a website in a given time period.

3. **Healthcare and Epidemiology:**
   - The Poisson distribution is commonly used in epidemiology to model the number of occurrences of a specific event, such as the number of disease cases in a population over a fixed period.

4. **Network Security:**
   - In cybersecurity, the Poisson distribution can be applied to model the rate of occurrence of security incidents, such as the number of intrusion attempts or malware infections.

5. **Traffic Flow and Transportation:**
   - The Poisson distribution is used to model traffic flow, where events are arrivals at a particular location or time. This can be relevant in predicting the number of vehicles passing through a toll booth or a checkpoint.

6. **Queueing Systems:**
   - Poisson processes are commonly used to model arrivals in queueing systems, where entities arrive randomly over time. This is applicable in scenarios like call centers, where calls arrive at random intervals.

7. **Rare Event Prediction:**
   - When dealing with rare events, such as fraud detection or equipment failures, the Poisson distribution can be a suitable choice for modeling the occurrence of these events over time.

8. **Bayesian Inference:**
   - In Bayesian machine learning, the Poisson distribution is often used as a prior distribution when modeling count data.

It's important to note that the Poisson distribution assumes that events occur independently and at a constant rate within the specified time or space interval. In practice, if these assumptions are not met, alternative distributions or modifications to the Poisson model may be considered. Additionally, the Poisson distribution can be extended to handle overdispersion using approaches like the negative binomial distribution.
